Paper 1005.5525v4:
Title: Efficient Local Search Algorithms for Known and New Neighborhoods for the Generalized Traveling Salesman Problem
Problem: The need to systematically define, analyze, and improve exploration algorithms for various GTSP neighborhoods (Cluster Optimization, TSP-inspired, and Fragment Optimization) in order to obtain high-quality solutions efficiently for larger GTSP instances.
Compared baselines: ['Basic (B) adaptations of TSP neighborhoods (2-opt, 3-opt, Insertion, Swap)', 'Basic with Cluster Optimization (co B)', 'Local (L) and Local with CO (co L) adaptations', 'Global (G) adaptations and their naive/simple versions', 'Cluster Optimization (CO) variants CO1‑CO4 (basic, with order optimization, with cluster reduction, hybrid)', 'Fragment Optimization algorithms F1 and F2 for different fragment sizes k', 'Existing literature methods: Fischetti et al. (1997), Renaud and Boctor (1998), Hu and Raidl (2008), Gutin and Karapetyan (2010), Snyder and Daskin (2006), etc.']
Results: ['Hybrid CO implementation (Algorithm\u202f6) reduces running time significantly, especially when γ>1, by combining cluster reduction and improved calculation order.', 'Global adaptation of 2-opt with supporting clusters and lower bound is >10× faster than the simple Global version and >100× faster than the naive version on large instances, while achieving solution errors around 5% on average.', 'Global 3-opt adaptation also shows substantial speed‑ups with comparable solution quality.', 'Fragment Optimization (F1 for k≤5, F2 for k>6) finds optimal fragment reordering in O(s²k!) or O(s²k²2ᵏ) time; empirical results show it is useful as a sub‑routine within larger heuristics.', 'Solution error percentages for the best adaptations (2-optG, 3-optG, InsG) are consistently lower than those of basic/local variants across test instances.']

Paper 2504.02190v2:
Title: A PTAS for Travelling Salesman Problem with Neighbourhoods Over Parallel Line Segments of Similar Length
Problem: The paper studies the Travelling Salesman Problem with Neighbourhoods (TSPN) where each neighbourhood is a parallel line segment (vertical) of length in [1, λ] for a fixed λ (unit length as a special case). The goal is to find a minimum‑length tour that visits at least one point on each segment. The challenge is to obtain a (1+ε)‑approximation despite previous constant‑factor bounds and APX‑hardness results for arbitrary orientations.
Compared baselines: ['Arkin and Hassin [8] gave a (3√2+1)-approximation for parallel unit‑length segments, later improved to 3√2 by [2]; this was the best known for over two decades.', 'Arora and Mitchell [6,7] presented PTASs for Euclidean TSP (the point case).', 'Various constant‑factor approximations for TSPN with fat objects, disjoint fat polygons, etc., were known.', 'APX‑hardness results: [20] shows TSPN for unit segments with arbitrary orientation is APX‑hard; [9] hardness for group Steiner tree implies hardness for general TSPN.', 'The authors’ PTAS improves upon the 3√2 approximation for parallel unit (or similar‑length) segments and matches the PTAS for point TSP as a special case.']
Results: The authors present a randomized (1+ε)-approximation algorithm for TSPN over n parallel line segments with lengths in [1, λ] (fixed λ) that runs in time n^{O((λ/ε)^3)}. The algorithm can be derandomized. As a corollary, they obtain a (2+ε)-approximation for axis‑parallel (horizontal or vertical) segments of bounded aspect ratio.

Paper 2507.04974v1:
Title: Approximation and Hardness of Polychromatic TSP
Problem: Study the approximability of Polychromatic TSP (PCTSP), where vertices are partitioned into equal-sized color classes and the goal is to find a minimum-weight Hamiltonian cycle that visits the color classes in a repeating order, focusing on metric graphs and Euclidean graphs in fixed dimension.
Compared baselines: The authors compare their results to classic TSP (Christofides 1.5‑approx, Karlin et al. improvement to 1.5−10^{−36}), the special case of edge weights 1,2 (7/6‑approx by Papadimitriou and Yannakakis), Euclidean TSP PTAS (Arora, Mitchell), Bipartite TSP (2.5‑approx by Anily and Hassin, improved to 2 by Chalasani et al.), and other chromatic TSP variants such as bicolored noncrossing Euclidean TSP (Gap‑ETH tight scheme by Dross et al.) and 3‑color TSP (constant factor by Baligács et al.). Their algorithm extends these ideas to an arbitrary number of color classes, while their hardness reduction shows that even Euclidean PCTSP in the plane inherits APX‑hardness from Max 2‑SAT, unlike classic Euclidean TSP which admits a PTAS.
Results: A polynomial‑time (3 − 2·10^{−36})-approximation algorithm for metric PCTSP; a proof that Euclidean PCTSP in the plane is APX‑hard and therefore does not admit a PTAS unless P=NP.

Paper 2603.21401v2:
Title: A Fast Quasi-Linear Heuristic for the Close-Enough Traveling Salesman Problem
Problem: The Close-Enough Traveling Salesman Problem (CETSP) is NP-hard; existing high-quality solvers are computationally expensive metaheuristics that do not scale to very large instances. The work seeks a fast heuristic with quasi-linear runtime that produces solution quality competitive with state-of-the-art methods while enabling application to much larger problem sizes.
Compared baselines: ['Lei and Hao (2024) genetic algorithm (current state-of-the-art CETSP solver)', 'SZVNS heuristic (Wang, Golden, and Wasil 2019)', 'Carrabs et al. carousel greedy heuristic (2020)', 'Di Placido, Archetti, and Cerrone (2022) genetic algorithm with SOCP', 'Cariou et al. (2023) geometric heuristic genetic algorithm', 'Exact/MIP/SOCP/branch-and-bound approaches (Behdani & Smith 2014; Carrabs et al. 2017; Coutinho et al. 2016; Zhang et al. 2023)']
Results: On the reconstructed Mennell (2009) benchmark suite, the proposed heuristic achieves solution gaps within 0−2% of the best-known results for nearly all instances, with one improvement of −1.49% on bonus1000. Gaps remain below 1% for Teams, TSPLIB, and ConcentricCircles series; up to 2.9% for RotatingDiamonds and up to 8.5% for Bubbles series. Empirical runtime shows expected O(n log n) scaling when tour size grows linearly with n, and sub‑O(n log n) behavior on random instances due to sublinear tour growth.

Paper 2311.00604v3:
Title: A Survey of Approximability Results for Traveling Salesman Problems using the TSP-T3CO Definition Scheme
Problem: The lack of a uniform, precise definition scheme for TSP variants makes it difficult to determine which approximability results apply to a given variant, hindering comparison of results and transfer of theory to practice.
Compared baselines: The paper compares TSP-T3CO to earlier classification schemes such as Reinelt's TSPLIB, Desrochers et al.'s four-field scheme, Bodin's VRP taxonomy, and scheduling problem classification schemes (α|β|γ), noting that those lack formal definitions, are not uniformly adopted, or do not separate problem definition from solution methods.
Results: Using TSP-T3CO 2025, the survey provides over 60 formally validated variant definitions and summarizes approximability and inapproximability bounds for variants including standard TSP, Path TSP, Bottleneck TSP, Maximum Scatter TSP, Generalized TSP, Clustered TSP, Traveling Purchaser Problem, Profitable Tour Problem, Quota TSP, Prize-Collecting TSP, Orienteering Problem, Time-dependent TSP, TSP with Time Windows, and Orienteering Problem with Time Windows, showing that metric/Euclidean/planar restrictions admit PTAS (1+ε) while general TSP remains inapproximable unless P=NP.

Paper 2509.00448v1:
Title: Approximating Graphic Multi-Path TSP and Graphic Ordered TSP
Problem: Given a unit-weight undirected graph and a set of source-sink (or ordered terminal) pairs, find walks that connect each pair and together visit every vertex while minimizing the total number of edge traversals.
Compared baselines: ['General Multi-Path TSP algorithm of [6] with approximation factor 1 + 2e^{-1/2} < 2.214', 'Graphic TSP approximations (Christofides 3/2, subsequent improvements down to ~1.4)', 'Trivial 2-approximation for Graphic Uncapacitated Multi-Depot VRP by doubling a spanning forest', 'Best known general Ordered TSP approximation factor 2 + e^{-1} ≈ 2.368']
Results: ['A randomized 2-approximation algorithm (derandomizable via conditional expectations) for Graphic Multi-Path TSP (Theorem 1.1)', 'The LP relaxation used has integrality gap at most 2 (Corollary 1)', '(1 + 2e^{-1})-approximation (≈1.736) for Graphic Ordered TSP (Theorem 1.2)', 'Reduction showing that any (2−δ)-approximation for Graphic Uncapacitated Multi-Depot VRP yields a (2−f(δ))-approximation for Graphic Multi-Path TSP (Theorem 1.3)']

Paper 1708.04215v4:
Title: A Constant-Factor Approximation Algorithm for the Asymmetric Traveling Salesman Problem
Problem: The main problem is to find a polynomial‑time algorithm that approximates the asymmetric traveling salesman problem (ATSP) within a constant factor of the optimum (or equivalently of the Held–Karp lower bound), despite the problem being NP‑hard to approximate within any factor without the triangle inequality and the lack of any constant‑factor guarantee prior to this work.
Compared baselines: ['Christofides’ algorithm (1976) for symmetric TSP gives a 3/2‑approximation, but does not apply to ATSP.', 'Frieze, Galbiati and Maffioli [FGM82] achieved an O(log n) approximation via repeated cycle covers.', 'Asadpour et al. [AGM[+] 17] improved this to O(log n / log log n) using thin spanning trees.', '[Sve15] gave a constant‑factor approximation for unweighted digraphs and node‑weighted graphs via Local‑Connectivity ATSP.', '[STV18a] proved Theorem 1.1 with an approximation ratio of 5500 using an earlier version of Subtour Partition Cover.', 'Traub and Vygen [TV20] later improved the ratio to 22 + ε and the integrality gap to 22 by refining the reductions.', 'Anari and Oveis Gharan [AG15] showed a non‑constructive O(poly log log n) upper bound on the integrality gap of the Held–Karp relaxation.', 'Known lower bounds: integrality gap ≥ 2 [CGK06] and inapproximability ≥ 75/74 [KLS13].']
Results: ['A polynomial‑time algorithm for ATSP that returns a tour of value at most 506 times the Held–Karp lower bound (Theorem 1.1).', 'Non‑constructively, the integrality gap of the Held–Karp relaxation is at most 319 (Theorem 11.1).', 'For the Asymmetric Traveling Salesman Path Problem (ATSPP) the paper yields a polynomial‑time algorithm with approximation ratio 2021 times the Held–Karp lower bound (Corollary 11.4) and integrality gap bounds of 1273 (Corollary 11.3).', 'The core technical contribution is a (4, 2·value(I) + lbI(B[̄]))‑light algorithm for Subtour Partition Cover on vertebrate pairs (Theorem 10.1), which via the reduction of Theorem 5.1 yields the ATSP approximation.']

Paper 1502.02051v2:
Title: Approximating ATSP by Relaxing Connectivity
Problem: The main problem is designing constant-factor approximation algorithms for the asymmetric traveling salesman problem (ATSP) under the triangle inequality, particularly improving upon the best known O(log n / log log n) approximation and the lower bound of 2 on the integrality gap of the Held-Karp relaxation.
Compared baselines: ['Frieze, Galbiati, and Maffiolo (1982): log₂(n)-approximation via cycle cover', 'Bläser (2003): 0.999 log₂(n)-approximation', 'Kaplan, Lewenstein, Shafrir, and Sviridenko (2003): (4/3) log₃(n) ≈ 0.84 log₂(n)-approximation', 'Feige and Singh (200?): (2/3) log₂(n)-approximation', 'Asadpour, Goemans, Madry, Oveis Gharan, and Saberi (2010): O(log n / log log n)-approximation', 'Oveis Gharan and Saberi (2011): constant-factor approximation for ATSP on planar and bounded genus graphs via O(1)-thin spanning trees', 'Anari and Oveis Gharan (2020): O(polylog log n) upper bound on the integrality gap of Held-Karp relaxation (non‑constructive)', 'Christofides (1976): 1.5‑approximation for symmetric TSP (STSP)']
Results: The paper shows a constant‑approximation algorithm for Node‑Weighted ATSP (shortest path metrics of node‑weighted digraphs). Specifically, the integrality gap of the Held‑Karp relaxation is at most 15, and for any ε > 0 there is a polynomial‑time algorithm that returns a tour of weight at most (27 + ε)·OPT_HK, where OPT_HK is the optimal value of the Held‑Karp relaxation.

Paper 1108.1130v2:
Title: 13/9-approximation for Graphic TSP
Problem: Improving the approximation factor for the graphic Travelling Salesman Problem (TSP) and its path variant (TSPP) beyond the state-of-the-art results, aiming to approach the conjectured integrality gap of the Held‑Karp relaxation.
Compared baselines: [{'method': 'Christofides algorithm', 'approximation_factor': '2'}, {'method': 'Oveis Gharan et al.', 'approximation_factor': '2 - ε (ε ≈ 10^{-12})'}, {'method': 'Mömke and Svensson', 'approximation_factor': '≈1.461 for graphic TSP, ≈1.586+ε for graphic TSPP'}]
Results: Achieves a 13/9 ≈ 1.444 approximation algorithm for graphic TSP and a (19/12 + ε) ≈ 1.583+ε approximation algorithm for graphic TSPP for any ε > 0.

Paper 2012.08379v5:
Title: Efficient PTAS for the Maximum Traveling Salesman Problem in a Metric Space of Fixed Doubling Dimension
Problem: The main research question is whether the maximum traveling salesman problem (Max TSP) admits a polynomial-time approximation scheme (PTAS) or an efficient PTAS (EPTAS) in metric spaces with bounded doubling dimension, i.e., to determine if a (1‑ε)-approximate solution can be found efficiently when the doubling dimension is fixed.
Compared baselines: The paper compares its results to prior approximation guarantees for Max TSP: 2/3 for arbitrary asymmetric weights, 7/9 for arbitrary symmetric weights, 35/44 for asymmetric metric case, and 7/8 for the metric case. It also references known PTAS for Euclidean TSP in fixed dimensions, the 5/6‑approximation of Kostochka and Serdyukov, exact DP for TSP, and Bartal et al.'s PTAS for TSP in doubling spaces. The work shows that before this paper no PTAS/EPTAS was known for Max TSP in doubling metrics.
Results: The authors prove Theorem 2: Max TSP in a metric space of doubling dimension at most dim admits an EPTAS that, for any ε∈(0,1), computes a (1‑ε)-approximate solution in time O(2^(2/ε)^(2dim+1) + n^3). They also prove Theorem 3: an O(n^3)-time algorithm with relative error at most (11/6)/n^(2dim+1), which becomes asymptotically exact when dim = o(log n).

